Option 1 (recommended): Config-driven JSON Pointer mapping (YAML → generic mapper)
1) Put the mapping in application.yml

You define: outgoingField → JSON Pointer (source path)

tdd:
  mapping:
    basePath: "/TDDMessage/TDDMExtended/HVP"
    fields:
      debitAccNo: "/DebitAccount/AccNb"
      debitAccType: "/DebitAccount/AccType"
      debitOffice: "/DebitAccount/Office"
      prodCode: "/ProdCode"
      mop: "/Mop"
      service: "/Service"
      extRef: "/ExtRef"

So your mapper always starts at HVP, and only pulls what you list.

2) Generic mapper (works with JsonNode)
@ConfigurationProperties(prefix = "tdd.mapping")
public class JsonMappingProps {
  private String basePath;                 // "/TDDMessage/TDDMExtended/HVP"
  private Map<String, String> fields = new LinkedHashMap<>(); // outgoing -> pointer
  // getters/setters
}
@Component
@EnableConfigurationProperties(JsonMappingProps.class)
public class ConfigDrivenJsonMapper {

  private final JsonMappingProps props;
  private final ObjectMapper om;

  public ConfigDrivenJsonMapper(JsonMappingProps props, ObjectMapper om) {
    this.props = props;
    this.om = om;
  }

  public ObjectNode map(JsonNode input) {
    ObjectNode out = om.createObjectNode();

    JsonNode hvp = input.at(props.getBasePath());
    if (hvp.isMissingNode() || hvp.isNull()) {
      // if you want: return empty object or throw, your call
      return out;
    }

    props.getFields().forEach((outField, ptr) -> {
      JsonNode v = hvp.at(ptr); // ptr is relative to HVP
      if (!v.isMissingNode()) {
        out.set(outField, v);   // preserves types (string/number/object/null)
      }
    });

    return out;
  }
}
3) Use it in Kafka Streams
@Bean
public Function<KStream<String, JsonNode>, KStream<String, JsonNode>> hvpTransform(
    ConfigDrivenJsonMapper mapper
) {
  return input -> input
      .mapValues(mapper::map);
}

✅ Pros:

Pure config mapping

Very fast, simple, no extra libs

Keeps types correctly (string vs number vs null)

Easy to add/remove fields without code changes

Option 2: JOLT spec (JSON “transform language”) in resources + selectable by config

If you want something more “ETL-like”, use JOLT (commonly used for JSON transforms).

Example JOLT spec file hvp-mapping.json:

[
  {
    "operation": "shift",
    "spec": {
      "TDDMessage": {
        "TDDMExtended": {
          "HVP": {
            "DebitAccount": {
              "AccNb": "debitAccNo",
              "AccType": "debitAccType",
              "Office": "debitOffice"
            },
            "ProdCode": "prodCode",
            "Mop": "mop"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
]

And you pick which spec to apply via YAML (per topic, per flow, etc.).

✅ Pros:

Transform logic is fully external spec

Can do more advanced reshaping than simple “copy these paths”

⚠️ Cons:

Extra dependency + slightly heavier runtime

Option 3: MapStruct + “partial config”

If your outgoing schema is a POJO/Avro class and stable, MapStruct is great, but it’s not purely config-driven unless you build a layer on top. It’s best when the mapping is “real code”, not “editable mapping”.

What I’d pick for your case

If your requirement is really: “HVP contains many fields; map only selected ones to outgoing schema; change it by config only” → Option 1 (JSON Pointer mapping) is the best balance of:

minimal dependencies

clear config

easy maintenance

works perfectly with Kafka Streams + JsonNode

Small extras you might need (common in real projects)
A) Default values if missing

Add in YAML:

tdd:
  mapping:
    defaults:
      service: "UNKNOWN"

Then if missing, set default.

B) Renaming + nested outgoing structure

If outgoing needs nesting (e.g., account.debit.no), allow dotted keys and build nodes accordingly.

C) Type coercion

If some outgoing fields must be string always (even if source is numeric), add metadata:

fields:
  amount:
    path: "/Amount"
    type: "string"

