1) How to “use filter + dedupe output” in NotificationProcessor

In Kafka Streams, each .process(...) receives the record after the previous processor already ran.

So your NotificationProcessor just reads the record like normal.

Preferred: build NotificationProcessor as a ContextualProcessor

That gives you access to:

headers

record metadata (topic/partition/offset)

forwarding to a different topic

try/catch per record

Example skeleton:

public class NotificationProcessor extends ContextualProcessor<String, JsonNode, String, JsonNode> {

  private final ConfigDrivenJsonMapper mapper; // the YAML pointer mapper
  private final ObjectMapper om;

  public NotificationProcessor(ConfigDrivenJsonMapper mapper, ObjectMapper om) {
    this.mapper = mapper;
    this.om = om;
  }

  @Override
  public void process(Record<String, JsonNode> record) {
    try {
      JsonNode in = record.value();

      // (optional) small extraction before mapping
      // e.g. MID for logging/routing
      String mid = in.at("/TDDMessage/TDDMExtended/HVP/Mid").asText(null);

      ObjectNode out = mapper.map(in);   // config-driven field picking
      // (optional) enrich
      if (mid != null) out.put("mid", mid);

      // forward to “success route”
      context().forward(record.withValue(out));

    } catch (Exception e) {
      // forward to “error route” with original payload
      ObjectNode err = buildError(record, e);
      context().forward(record.withValue(err), To.child("error-sink"));
      // OR: put a header and let topicNameExtractor route it
    }
  }

  private ObjectNode buildError(Record<String, JsonNode> record, Exception e) {
    ObjectNode err = om.createObjectNode();
    err.put("errorType", e.getClass().getSimpleName());
    err.put("errorMessage", safeMsg(e));
    err.set("original", record.value()); // keep full context (or truncate if huge)
    err.put("key", record.key());

    // metadata (super useful for replay)
    err.put("srcTopic", context().topic());
    err.put("partition", context().partition());
    err.put("offset", context().offset());

    return err;
  }

  private String safeMsg(Exception e) {
    String msg = e.getMessage();
    return msg == null ? "n/a" : msg.substring(0, Math.min(msg.length(), 500));
  }
}

Then in topology:

stream = input
  .process(FilterProcessor::new)
  .process(dedupProcessorSupplier)
  .process(() -> new NotificationProcessor(mapper, objectMapper),
           Named.as("notification-transform"),
           "error-sink"); // optional named child

Important: if you use To.child("error-sink"), you need to attach sinks (see error handling section below).

2) “Parsing JSON / deserializing handled automatically” — where errors actually happen

Even if you’re using JsonNode, failures can happen in two places:

A) At Kafka consumer deserialization

This is before your topology sees the record.

Fix with ErrorHandlingDeserializer (Spring Kafka)

Or set Streams deserialization exception handler (Kafka Streams)

B) Inside your processors

null nodes

missing paths

type coercion (asText() on object, etc.)

your custom code

So you want both: a deserialization handler + processor try/catch.

3) Best error-handling approach for Streams (pragmatic)
Level 1: Deserialization handler

In Streams config:

If you want to skip bad records (and keep app running):

default.deserialization.exception.handler = LogAndContinueExceptionHandler

If you want to stop on bad records:

LogAndFailExceptionHandler

Spring Boot property style (example):

spring:
  kafka:
    streams:
      properties:
        default.deserialization.exception.handler: org.apache.kafka.streams.errors.LogAndContinueExceptionHandler

But skipping is risky unless you also emit to an error topic.

If you need an error topic for deser failures, common pattern is:

consume as byte[] / String

parse inside processor with try/catch

route to error topic yourself
(so you never lose the raw bytes)

Level 2: Processing exception handling (inside NotificationProcessor)

The try/catch in process() is your “DLQ for mapping logic”.

4) Routing to success vs error with your topicNameExtractor

Since you’re already doing stream.to(topicNameExtractor), easiest is:

A) Add a header like route=ERROR or error=true

Then your topicNameExtractor decides topic by header.

In processor:

Headers headers = record.headers();
headers.add("route", "ERROR".getBytes(StandardCharsets.UTF_8));
context().forward(record.withValue(err));

In extractor:

if route=ERROR → notifications.error

else → notifications.out

This keeps topology simple: one .to(topicNameExtractor).

B) Or do explicit branching
KStream<String, JsonNode>[] branches = stream.branch(
  (k,v) -> v.has("errorType"),
  (k,v) -> true
);

branches[0].to("notifications.error");
branches[1].to("notifications.out");

This is super readable and avoids header games.

5) “Mapping + extract some values before forwarding”

You already saw the in.at("/...") approach. I recommend standardizing it:

Small helper (safe extraction)
public final class Jsons {
  private Jsons() {}

  public static String text(JsonNode n, String ptr) {
    JsonNode v = n.at(ptr);
    return (v.isMissingNode() || v.isNull()) ? null : v.asText();
  }

  public static Long longVal(JsonNode n, String ptr) {
    JsonNode v = n.at(ptr);
    return (v.isMissingNode() || v.isNull()) ? null : v.asLong();
  }
}

Use:

String mid = Jsons.text(in, "/TDDMessage/TDDMExtended/HVP/Mid");
If you want extraction also config-driven

Extend YAML:

tdd:
  mapping:
    extract:
      mid: "/TDDMessage/TDDMExtended/HVP/Mid"
      mop: "/TDDMessage/TDDMExtended/HVP/Mop"

Then you can add headers/fields without code changes.

6) Practical “good defaults” for filter + dedupe + error flow

FilterProcessor: if invalid business rule → route to error topic with reason FILTERED

DedupeProcessor: duplicates → drop (or route to “duplicates” topic if you need audit)

NotificationProcessor:

map via config

enrich with mid, eventTs

exceptions → error payload (include original + metadata)
